=========================================================
RULE OF FIVE - COMPLETE INTERVIEW EXAMPLE
=========================================================

#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

class Test
{
private:
    int* ptr;

public:

    // 1. Constructor
    Test(int val = 0)
    {
        ptr = new int(val);
        cout << "Constructor\n";
    }

    // 2. Destructor
    ~Test()
    {
        delete ptr;
        cout << "Destructor\n";
    }

    // 3. Copy Constructor
    Test(const Test& other)
    {
        cout << "Copy Constructor\n";
        ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
    }

    // 4. Copy Assignment Operator
    Test& operator=(const Test& other)
    {
        cout << "Copy Assignment Operator\n";

        if(this != &other)
        {
            delete ptr;
            ptr = new int(*other.ptr);
        }

        return *this;
    }

    // 5. Move Constructor
    Test(Test&& other) noexcept
    {
        cout << "Move Constructor\n";

        ptr = other.ptr;
        other.ptr = nullptr;
    }

    // 6. Move Assignment Operator
    Test& operator=(Test&& other) noexcept
    {
        cout << "Move Assignment Operator\n";

        if(this != &other)
        {
            delete ptr;

            ptr = other.ptr;
            other.ptr = nullptr;
        }

        return *this;
    }

    void display() const
    {
        if(ptr)
            cout << *ptr << endl;
        else
            cout << "nullptr\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test t1(10);

    // Copy Constructor
    Test t2 = t1;

    // Copy Assignment
    Test t3(20);
    t3 = t1;

    // Move Constructor
    Test t4 = std::move(t1);

    // Move Assignment
    Test t5(50);
    t5 = std::move(t2);

    t3.display();
    t4.display();
    t5.display();
}

=========================================================
RULE OF FIVE - INTERVIEW QUESTIONS & ANSWERS
=========================================================

Q1. What is Rule of Five?

A:
If a class manages a resource (dynamic memory, file,
socket, mutex, etc.) and defines one special member
function, it usually needs all five:

1. Destructor
2. Copy Constructor
3. Copy Assignment Operator
4. Move Constructor
5. Move Assignment Operator

---------------------------------------------------------

Q2. What is Rule of Three?

A:
If a class defines any one of:

1. Destructor
2. Copy Constructor
3. Copy Assignment Operator

it usually needs all three.

Rule of Five is an extension of Rule of Three in C++11.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q3. Why was Rule of Three extended to Rule of Five?

A:
C++11 introduced move semantics.

Therefore:

4. Move Constructor
5. Move Assignment Operator

were added.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q4. What is a Copy Constructor?

A:
A constructor that creates a new object from an
existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName(const ClassName& other);

Example:

Test t2 = t1;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q5. What is a Copy Assignment Operator?

A:
Copies data into an already existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName& operator=(const ClassName& other);

Example:

t2 = t1;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q6. Difference between Copy Constructor and
Copy Assignment Operator?

A:

Copy Constructor:
Creates a NEW object.

Example:

Test t2 = t1;

Copy Assignment:
Assigns to an EXISTING object.

Example:

t2 = t1;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q7. What is a Move Constructor?

A:
Transfers ownership of resources from one object
to another without copying.

Syntax:

ClassName(ClassName&& other);

Example:

Test t2 = std::move(t1);

---------------------------------------------------------

Q8. What is a Move Assignment Operator?

A:
Transfers ownership of resources into an already
existing object.

Syntax:

ClassName& operator=(ClassName&& other);

Example:

t2 = std::move(t1);

---------------------------------------------------------

Q9. What is std::move()?

A:
std::move does not move anything by itself.

It converts an lvalue into an rvalue reference,
allowing move constructor or move assignment
to be called.

Example:

Test t2 = std::move(t1);

---------------------------------------------------------

Q10. Why set source pointer to nullptr after move?

A:

ptr = other.ptr;
other.ptr = nullptr;

This prevents both objects from owning the same
resource and avoids double deletion.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q11. Why is self-assignment check needed?

A:

if(this != &other)

Protects against:

obj = obj;

Without the check, the object may delete its own
resource and then try to copy from itself.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q12. Why is self-assignment check not needed in
Move Constructor?

A:
Move Constructor creates a NEW object.

Source and destination can never be the same object.

Therefore:

this == &other

is impossible.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q13. What is shallow copy?

A:
Only pointer addresses are copied.

Example:

obj2.ptr = obj1.ptr;

Both objects point to the same memory.

Problems:

1. Shared ownership
2. Double delete
3. Undefined behavior

---------------------------------------------------------

Q14. What is deep copy?

A:
Allocate new memory and copy actual data.

Example:

ptr = new int(*other.ptr);

Each object owns separate memory.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q15. Why does shallow copy cause double delete?

A:

obj1.ptr ----+
             |
             v
           Memory
             ^
             |
obj2.ptr ----+

When destructors run:

delete ptr;
delete ptr;

Same memory is deleted twice.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q16. Why pass Copy Constructor parameter as
const reference?

A:

Correct:

Test(const Test& other);

Wrong:

Test(Test other);

Passing by value invokes copy constructor again,
causing infinite recursion.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q17. Why return reference from assignment operator?

A:

Test& operator=(const Test& other);

Allows chaining:

a = b = c;

Returning reference avoids unnecessary copies.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q18. Why mark move operations noexcept?

A:

Test(Test&& other) noexcept

STL containers such as vector prefer move
operations only when they are noexcept.

Improves performance during reallocation.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q19. What happens after moving an object?

A:

The moved-from object remains valid but its state
is unspecified.

Common practice:

other.ptr = nullptr;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q20. Can Copy Constructor call Copy Assignment?

A:
No.

Copy Constructor initializes a new object.

Copy Assignment works on an already existing object.

They serve different purposes.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q21. Can Move Constructor call Move Assignment?

A:
Possible but not recommended.

Usually implement them separately for clarity
and efficiency.

---------------------------------------------------------

Q22. What is resource ownership?

A:
Responsibility for releasing a resource.

Example:

int* ptr = new int(10);

Owner must call:

delete ptr;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q23. Why does unique_ptr delete copy operations?

A:

unique_ptr provides exclusive ownership.

Two unique_ptr objects cannot own the same resource.

Therefore:

unique_ptr(const unique_ptr&) = delete;

unique_ptr& operator=(const unique_ptr&) = delete;

---------------------------------------------------------

Q24. Why does unique_ptr allow move operations?

A:

Ownership can be transferred safely.

Example:

unique_ptr<int> p2 = std::move(p1);

After move:

p1 -> nullptr
p2 -> owns resource

---------------------------------------------------------

Q25. What is the most common Rule of Five interview
example?

A:

A class owning dynamic memory:

class Test
{
    int* ptr;
};

Such classes require:

Destructor
Copy Constructor
Copy Assignment
Move Constructor
Move Assignment

=========================================================
ONE-LINE REVISION
=========================================================

Copy Constructor:
Creates a new object from an existing object.

Copy Assignment:
Copies into an existing object.

Move Constructor:
Transfers ownership while creating a new object.

Move Assignment:
Transfers ownership into an existing object.

Shallow Copy:
Copies pointer addresses only.

Deep Copy:
Allocates new memory and copies actual data.

Rule of Three:
Destructor + Copy Constructor + Copy Assignment.

Rule of Five:
Rule of Three + Move Constructor + Move Assignment.

std::move:
Converts lvalue to rvalue reference.

noexcept:
Enables efficient moves in STL containers.

unique_ptr Copy:
Deleted because ownership must be unique.

unique_ptr Move:
Allowed because ownership can be transferred.
